In today's interconnected world, the internet has become an integral part of our lives. We use it to communicate, learn, work, and play. But with the vast opportunities of the online world come responsibilities. This is where the concept of digital citizenship comes in.

Digital citizenship refers to the responsible use of technology and the ethical behavior exhibited by individuals online. It encompasses a range of principles and practices that guide our interactions in the digital realm.

This lesson will explore the aspects of digital citizenship including digital literacy, etiquette, security, and your rights and responsibilities.

props.text:
Learning Objectives

By the end of this lesson, students will be able to:

  • Define digital citizenship and explain its importance in today's society.
  • Identify key elements of digital citizenship, including digital literacy, etiquette, security, rights and responsibilities, and health and wellness.
  • Demonstrate proper online etiquette by communicating respectfully and responsibly in online interactions.
  • Apply critical thinking skills to evaluate online information and make informed decisions.

Essential Questions

The essential questions addressed in this lesson include:

  • What is digital citizenship, and why is it important?
  • What are our rights and responsibilities in the digital world?
  • How can we communicate effectively and respectfully online?

1. Watch: Watch the Digital Citizenship video and take notes on key ideas.
  2. Discuss: Actively engage in the discussion about digital citizenship, sharing your thoughts and questions.
  3. Read: Read and analyze real-life scenarios about online situations and discuss the best course of action.
  4. Create: Design a personal pledge outlining your commitment to responsible online behavior.
  5. Assess: Test your knowledge of digital citizenship concepts with a short online quiz.
